> Pescado Veracruz hails from the city of the same name, Veracruz, Mexico. Founded by the Spanish, the city continues to be Mexico's largest and busiest port. As a result, many European ingredients—such as olives—were introduced to Mexico via trade. This recipe is so satisfyingly simple to prepare—I never get tired of eating and making it. –Chef Robert Stauning

== Cook the Rice ==

Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. In a #small pot{}, bring @water{1%cup} and a large
pinch of @salt{1%pinch} to a boil. Add the @basmati rice{1/2%cup}, cover, and reduce
to a low simmer for about ~{15%minutes}, until tender. Keep covered until the rest
of the meal is ready.

== Prep the Ingredients ==

Halve, peel, and finely dice the @yellow onion{1}(peeled and finely diced). Mince or
grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(minced). Slice the @mixed olives{1%ounce} and
@green olives{1%ounce} into rings. Core and dice the @roma tomato{1}(cored and diced).
Finely chop the @parsley{1/4%ounce}(finely chopped), reserving a few leaves for garnish.

== Roast the Grape Tomatoes ==

Toss the @grape tomatoes{4%ounce} on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of
@olive oil{1%tbsp} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Place in the
oven for ~{15-20%minutes}, until burst and slightly charred.

== Make the Veracruz Sauce ==

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in another #medium pot{} over medium heat. Add the
onion, garlic, and plum tomato to the pot and cook, tossing, for ~{4-5%minutes},
until soft. Add the olives, @veggie stock concentrate{1%unit}, @thyme{}, and
@water{1/2%cup} to the pot. Simmer for ~{1-2%minutes}, until slightly thickened.
Season with pepper. Remove from the heat and cover to keep warm.

== Cook the Cod ==

Season the @cod fillets{12%ounce} on all sides with @salt{pinch}, @pepper{pinch},
and a drizzle of olive oil. Place onto the baking sheet with the tomatoes and
bake for ~{7-8%minutes}, until flaky and opaque.

== Plate ==

Reheat the Veracruz sauce, if necessary. Place the cod on a bed of rice and top
with the burst tomatoes, Veracruz sauce, and a sprinkle of parsley. Enjoy!